console.log('hello from my-tool');
```

`#!/usr/bin/env node` lets the OS pick up `node` from the user's PATH (works across nvm, brew, system installs). Make the file executable with `chmod +x ./bin/my-tool.js`. On publish, npm marks anything listed under `bin` as executable in the installed package.

```ts
import { z, ZodSchema } from 'zod';

export async function typedFetch<T>(
  url: string,
  schema: ZodSchema<T>,
  init?: RequestInit,
): Promise<T> {
  const res = await fetch(url, init);
  if (!res.ok) {
    throw new Error(`HTTP ${res.status} for ${url}`);
  }
  const body = await res.json();
  return schema.parse(body); // throws ZodError on mismatch
}
```

`ZodSchema<T>` flows the inferred type to the return. `parse` throws a `ZodError` on mismatch — the caller can catch it and inspect `err.issues` for field-level detail. Use `safeParse` if the caller prefers discriminated-union handling.

```ts
export type Result<T, E> =
  | { readonly ok: true; readonly value: T }
  | { readonly ok: false; readonly error: E };

export const ok = <T>(value: T): Result<T, never> => ({ ok: true, value });
export const err = <E>(error: E): Result<never, E> => ({ ok: false, error });

export function map<T, U, E>(r: Result<T, E>, f: (t: T) => U): Result<U, E> {
  return r.ok ? ok(f(r.value)) : r;
}
```

The `readonly` tags prevent callers from mutating the discriminator. `ok` returns `Result<T, never>` and `err` returns `Result<never, E>`, which flow cleanly through `map` without widening. `map` short-circuits on the err branch — it's the same semantics as `fp-ts` Either's `map`.

```ts
export function debounce<T extends (...args: any[]) => any>(
  fn: T,
  ms: number,
): T {
  let timer: ReturnType<typeof setTimeout> | null = null;
  const debounced = (...args: Parameters<T>): void => {
    if (timer !== null) clearTimeout(timer);
    timer = setTimeout(() => { fn(...args); timer = null; }, ms);
  };
  return debounced as T;
}
```

The return type loses `fn`'s original return type on purpose — debounced calls don't return synchronously (the real call happens later). If you need the eventual return, change the wrapper to return `Promise<ReturnType<T>>` and resolve inside the timer. Using `ReturnType<typeof setTimeout>` keeps this portable across Node (`Timeout`) and DOM (`number`) types.
